Sentencas: Modeling the oxygen partial pressure at the interfaces of solid oxide electrolysis cells is essential to understand their degradation.
Titulo: Insights into strontium zirconate-induced interface pressures in solid oxide electrolysis cells

Sentencas: Here we present a bilayer electrolyte equivalent circuit model that does not assume continuity of the oxygen chemical potential at the electrolyte interface, in line with experimental results.
Titulo: Insights into strontium zirconate-induced interface pressures in solid oxide electrolysis cells

Sentencas: We use the model to assess the assumption that strontium zirconate growth is responsible for oxygen electrode interface pressure increases and delamination.
Titulo: Insights into strontium zirconate-induced interface pressures in solid oxide electrolysis cells

Sentencas: We find that 5% Y-doped strontium zirconate does not drive fracture for accumulations up to 250 nm except at 800 degrees C and 1.6 V. With a low electronic conductivity, 5% La-doped strontium zirconate shows a region of stability where increased thickness actually stabilizes the interface pressure.
Titulo: Insights into strontium zirconate-induced interface pressures in solid oxide electrolysis cells

Sentencas: We also highlight the importance of modeling interface stability with the proper electronic conductivity.
Titulo: Insights into strontium zirconate-induced interface pressures in solid oxide electrolysis cells

Sentencas: Finally, we present interface stability requirements and contextualize the strontium zirconate composition results in terms of interface stabilization strategies.
Titulo: Insights into strontium zirconate-induced interface pressures in solid oxide electrolysis cells
